</tr>
</table>
<p>In <a href="/wiki/Telecommunications" title="Telecommunications" class="mw-redirect">telecommunications</a>, <b>frequency modulation</b> (<b>FM</b>) conveys <a href="/wiki/Information" title="Information">information</a> over a <a href="/wiki/Carrier_wave" title="Carrier wave">carrier wave</a> by varying its <a href="/wiki/Frequency" title="Frequency">frequency</a> (contrast this with <a href="/wiki/Amplitude_modulation" title="Amplitude modulation">amplitude modulation</a>, in which the <a href="/wiki/Amplitude" title="Amplitude">amplitude</a> of the carrier is varied while its frequency remains constant). In <a href="/wiki/Analog_signal" title="Analog signal">analog</a> applications, the instantaneous frequency of the carrier is directly proportional to the instantaneous value of the input signal. <a href="/wiki/Digital" title="Digital">Digital</a> <a href="/wiki/Data" title="Data">data</a> can be sent by shifting the carrier's frequency among a set of discrete values, a technique known as <a href="/wiki/Frequency-shift_keying" title="Frequency-shift keying">frequency-shift keying</a>.</p>
